The power set of a set S is the set of all possible subsets of S, including the empty set and S itself. In this case, S = {1, 2, 3}. To find the power set of S, we list all possible subsets:

1. {}
2. {1}
3. {2}
4. {3}
5. {1, 2}
6. {1, 3}
7. {2, 3}
8. {1, 2, 3}

There are 8 elements in the power set of S.

Now, let's compare the size of the power set of S to the size of S itself. The size of S is 3 (since it has 3 elements: 1, 2, and 3), and the size of the power set of S is 8. Since 8 > 3, this supports the statement that the power set of a set is always larger than the set itself. In general, for a set with n elements, its power set will have 2^n elements, which is always greater than n for any non-negative integer n.
